ETYMOLOGY: The name of this species is from the Latin for the Roman guardian of newborn children (Deverra) and is symbolized by a broom for sweeping away evil influences (
Jordan , 1993
); used in apposition.

ETYMOLOGY: Named for the many armed Hindu goddess Durga, who is depicted as a woman riding on a lion or tiger and in whose hands are weapons. In later Hindu tradition, particularly in northern India , Durga is linked with the fertility of crops and is celebrated at harvest time in the Durga Puja (
Jordan , 1993
); used in apposition.

